1 (a) There is a Class B–Stadium (baseball stadium) beer, wine, and liquor license.
2 (b) The Board may issue the license to:
3 (1) the owner of a professional team franchise, whether the franchise is a
4 partnership, corporation, or limited liability company; or
5 (2) a private concessionaire that is under contract with the county or a
6 professional baseball team franchise.
7 (c) (1) The license authorizes the license holder to sell beer, wine, and liquor
8 on the premises of a baseball stadium owned or operated by the county, EXCLUDING ANY
9 PARKING AREAS, to individuals present at a baseball game or other event held at the
10 stadium.
11 (2) (i) Except as provided in subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, beer,
12 wine, and liquor shall be served in plastic, [Styrofoam, or] paper, OR OTHER NONGLASS
13 containers on the stadium premises.
14 (ii) Beer, wine, and liquor may be served in glass containers in an
15 enclosed stadium dining area in which patrons are seated.
16 (3) A patron[:
17 (i)] may consume and carry beer [and], wine, AND LIQUOR
18 anywhere on the stadium premises, EXCLUDING ANY PARKING AREAS[; but
19 (ii) 1. may consume liquor only in an enclosed stadium dining
20 area or bar; and
21 2. may not carry liquor out of the enclosed stadium dining
22 area or bar].
23 (4) The license holder may not allow an individual to carry alcoholic
24 beverages onto or from the licensed premises.
25 (d) Except as provided in regulations adopted under subsection (e) of this section,
26 the license holder may sell beer, wine, and liquor during the hours and days as set out for
27 a Class B beer, wine, and liquor license under § 18–2004 of this title.
28 (e) The Board may adopt regulations relating to:
29 (1) the manner of serving alcoholic beverages;
30 (2) the number of outlets authorized to serve alcoholic beverages; and

